        <strong>Quick start:</strong> Plan your first night, keep digital copies of documents, and set up mobile data before you land.
      </div>

      <h2 id="top10">10 beginner tips</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Plan your first night</strong> with a simple arrival plan: transport, check-in, food.</li>
        <li><strong>Back up key documents</strong> in cloud storage and offline.</li>
        <li><strong>Sort adapters and data</strong> before departure: plug type, eSIM, SIM, hotspot.</li>
        <li><strong>Notify your bank</strong> and bring at least one backup card.</li>
        <li><strong>Use a money split</strong> cash for small shops, card for big spends.</li>
        <li><strong>Pack one emergency set</strong> in carry-on: meds, charger, basic clothes.</li>
        <li><strong>Learn 10 phrases</strong> plus address and emergency numbers.</li>
        <li><strong>Keep your day bag simple</strong> and avoid flashing valuables.</li>
        <li><strong>Save offline maps</strong> and your accommodation address.</li>
        <li><strong>Leave buffer time</strong> in your schedule. First trips feel slower.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2 id="short">Short tips</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Write a tiny must-do list. 3 things per day is enough.</li>
        <li>Choose shoes first. Everything else follows.</li>
        <li>Keep receipts and booking emails in one folder.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="safety">Safety basics</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Share your itinerary with one trusted person.</li>
        <li>Use a crossbody bag or zipped backpack in crowded areas.</li>
        <li>Know the local emergency number for your destination.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="packing">Packing tips</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Pack layers. Korea weather changes fast by season.</li>
        <li>Bring a compact power bank and a multi-port charger.</li>
        <li>Use small pouches to keep cables and toiletries tidy.</li>
      </ul>

